{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-post-js","path":"/mastering-paper/erasing/","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"frontmatter":{"title":"Mastering Paper for iOS: erasing and how to undo","date":"2014-10-25T00:00:00.000Z","date_pretty":"October 25th, 2014","date_from_now":"6 years ago","last_modified_at":"2020-01-06T15:09:50.000Z","last_modified_at_from_now":"6 months ago","path":"/mastering-paper/erasing/","author":null,"excerpt":"Learn how to use Paper's eraser tool to correct and cover-up mistakes.","tags":["Paper for iOS","Pencil by 53","tutorial","Apple"],"image":{"childImageSharp":{"fluid":{"aspectRatio":2.433628318584071,"src":"/static/3547632dd3b62fbe80ec963bbc4d561d/fc20c/paper-53-erasing-feature.jpg","srcSet":"/static/3547632dd3b62fbe80ec963bbc4d561d/6e883/paper-53-erasing-feature.jpg 275w,\n/static/3547632dd3b62fbe80ec963bbc4d561d/a09ef/paper-53-erasing-feature.jpg 550w,\n/static/3547632dd3b62fbe80ec963bbc4d561d/fc20c/paper-53-erasing-feature.jpg 1100w,\n/static/3547632dd3b62fbe80ec963bbc4d561d/356ef/paper-53-erasing-feature.jpg 1280w","sizes":"(max-width: 1100px) 100vw, 1100px"},"fixed":{"src":"/static/3547632dd3b62fbe80ec963bbc4d561d/fc20c/paper-53-erasing-feature.jpg","height":452,"width":1100}}},"toc":true,"comments":true,"comments_locked":true,"hide_meta":null},"id":"ebd1971c-3dbb-5064-aa41-d69b2a69d21d","html":"<p>One of those tools that is easily forgotten about is the eraser — the utensils used to make marks tend to get more attention than those that undo them. At first blush, erasing in an app like <a href=\"https://paper.bywetransfer.com/\">Paper by FiftyThree</a> may appear limiting and simplistic. Paired with <a href=\"https://amzn.to/2FpYrGJ\">FiftyThree’s Pencil stylus</a> and a little creativity do the possibilities really begin to fly.</p>\n<h2 id=\"eraser-tool-101\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#eraser-tool-101\" aria-label=\"eraser tool 101 permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Eraser tool 101</h2>\n<p>Opening Paper’s tool tray you will find that the eraser is the first tool on the left.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; background-color: var(--input-background-color); max-width: 900px;\"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 40.72727272727273%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image lazyload\"\n        alt=\"screenshot of the tool tray in Paper with eraser highlighted\"\n        title=\"screenshot of the tool tray in Paper with eraser highlighted\"\n        data-src=\"/static/5126c118c77c01a8f7681cde7ce3990b/062c0/paper-53-eraser-tool-tray.jpg\"\n        data-srcset=\"/static/5126c118c77c01a8f7681cde7ce3990b/16841/paper-53-eraser-tool-tray.jpg 275w,\n/static/5126c118c77c01a8f7681cde7ce3990b/50c97/paper-53-eraser-tool-tray.jpg 550w,\n/static/5126c118c77c01a8f7681cde7ce3990b/062c0/paper-53-eraser-tool-tray.jpg 900w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 900px) 100vw, 900px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p>Owners of <a href=\"https://amzn.to/2FpYrGJ\"><strong>FiftyThree’s Pencil</strong></a> have the added benefit of a dedicated eraser on the top of the stylus. Now you can flow between drawing and erasing by simply flipping Pencil around as you would a <em>real pencil</em>. Of course you can still select the eraser from the tool try and use Pencil’s pointed tip to erase — but who does that?</p>\n<figure>\n  <span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\" style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; background-color: var(--input-background-color); max-width: 900px;\">\n      <span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\" style=\"padding-bottom: 56.36363636363636%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; display: block;\"></span>\n  <img class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image lazyload\" alt=\"detail of Pencil&apos;s eraser and replacement\" title=\"detail of Pencil&apos;s eraser and replacement\" data-src=\"/static/e33f8187cab4f87ddc546e29f7b703f2/062c0/paper-53-eraser-replacement.jpg\" data-srcset=\"/static/e33f8187cab4f87ddc546e29f7b703f2/16841/paper-53-eraser-replacement.jpg 275w,\n/static/e33f8187cab4f87ddc546e29f7b703f2/50c97/paper-53-eraser-replacement.jpg 550w,\n/static/e33f8187cab4f87ddc546e29f7b703f2/062c0/paper-53-eraser-replacement.jpg 900w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 900px) 100vw, 900px\" style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\" loading=\"lazy\">\n    </span>\n  <figcaption><p>Just like the tip, Pencil&apos;s eraser is user replaceable.</p></figcaption>\n</figure>\n<h3 id=\"how-speed-affects-erasing\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#how-speed-affects-erasing\" aria-label=\"how speed affects erasing permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>How speed affects erasing</h3>\n<p>All of the tools in Paper react to the speed at which you use them — the eraser is no different. When dragging your finger or stylus across the iPad slowly, the eraser will be at its thinnest width. As you increase the speed at which you move, the wider the eraser’s size becomes.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; background-color: var(--input-background-color); max-width: 880px;\"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 48.72727272727273%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image lazyload\"\n        alt=\"erasing from thin to thick\"\n        title=\"erasing from thin to thick\"\n        data-src=\"/static/b027efe9cb04c348a178b0f04982df5e/48184/paper-53-eraser-thick-thin.jpg\"\n        data-srcset=\"/static/b027efe9cb04c348a178b0f04982df5e/16841/paper-53-eraser-thick-thin.jpg 275w,\n/static/b027efe9cb04c348a178b0f04982df5e/50c97/paper-53-eraser-thick-thin.jpg 550w,\n/static/b027efe9cb04c348a178b0f04982df5e/48184/paper-53-eraser-thick-thin.jpg 880w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 880px) 100vw, 880px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<h3 id=\"how-surface-pressure-affects-erasing\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#how-surface-pressure-affects-erasing\" aria-label=\"how surface pressure affects erasing permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>How Surface Pressure affects erasing</h3>\n<p>In <a href=\"/mastering-paper/pencil-53-review/#what-about-the-eraser\">my review of Pencil</a> I dinged the dedicated eraser as a missed opportunity by not adding any new capabilities to the tool. Well when FiftyThree updated Paper to include the new <strong>Surface Pressure</strong><sup id=\"fnref-1\"><a href=\"#fn-1\" class=\"footnote-ref\">1</a></sup> feature, Pencil’s eraser got a serious upgrade.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; background-color: var(--input-background-color); max-width: 600px;\"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 90.18181818181819%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image lazyload\"\n        alt=\"erasing with the corner\"\n        title=\"erasing with the corner\"\n        data-src=\"/static/514baa3db7cb274fd566b425bc72828c/f6133/paper-53-erasing-corner.jpg\"\n        data-srcset=\"/static/514baa3db7cb274fd566b425bc72828c/16841/paper-53-erasing-corner.jpg 275w,\n/static/514baa3db7cb274fd566b425bc72828c/50c97/paper-53-erasing-corner.jpg 550w,\n/static/514baa3db7cb274fd566b425bc72828c/f6133/paper-53-erasing-corner.jpg 600w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p>Erasing with the corner versus the entire width of Pencil’s eraser.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; background-color: var(--input-background-color); max-width: 600px;\"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 90.18181818181819%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image lazyload\"\n        alt=\"erasing with the entire edge\"\n        title=\"erasing with the entire edge\"\n        data-src=\"/static/fa2246a714e124f88879321617a3ba45/f6133/paper-53-erasing-wide.jpg\"\n        data-srcset=\"/static/fa2246a714e124f88879321617a3ba45/16841/paper-53-erasing-wide.jpg 275w,\n/static/fa2246a714e124f88879321617a3ba45/50c97/paper-53-erasing-wide.jpg 550w,\n/static/fa2246a714e124f88879321617a3ba45/f6133/paper-53-erasing-wide.jpg 600w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p>Pencil’s eraser now changes size depending on how much of it makes contact with the iPad’s screen. Touching the corner of the eraser to the screen will remove a small portion of your drawing. While swipes with the wider edge erase in broader strokes.</p>\n<figure>\n  <span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\" style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; background-color: var(--input-background-color); max-width: 900px;\">\n      <span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\" style=\"padding-bottom: 66.18181818181819%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; display: block;\"></span>\n  <img class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image lazyload\" alt=\"eraser sizes\" title=\"eraser sizes\" data-src=\"/static/059d4e086fd75f9ea054ad1ecc2e278d/062c0/paper-53-eraser-sizes.jpg\" data-srcset=\"/static/059d4e086fd75f9ea054ad1ecc2e278d/16841/paper-53-eraser-sizes.jpg 275w,\n/static/059d4e086fd75f9ea054ad1ecc2e278d/50c97/paper-53-eraser-sizes.jpg 550w,\n/static/059d4e086fd75f9ea054ad1ecc2e278d/062c0/paper-53-eraser-sizes.jpg 900w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 900px) 100vw, 900px\" style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\" loading=\"lazy\">\n    </span>\n  <figcaption><p>Pencil&#x2019;s eraser offers way more flexibility in size than the default eraser.</p>\n</figcaption></figure>\n<p>A Surface Pressure enabled eraser can be made quite small, allowing you to sneak into tighter spaces. A trick the normal eraser tool wishes it could pull off.</p>\n<h3 id=\"how-pressure-sensitivity-affects-erasing\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#how-pressure-sensitivity-affects-erasing\" aria-label=\"how pressure sensitivity affects erasing permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>How pressure sensitivity affects erasing</h3>\n<p>Currently the <a href=\"/mastering-paper/pogo-connect-smart-pen/\">Pogo Connect</a> is the only pressure sensitive stylus Paper supports. When paired to Paper you can vary the size of the eraser (and the other tools) by applying  pressure to the tip as you drag it across the screen.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; background-color: var(--input-background-color); max-width: 900px;\"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 32.36363636363636%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image lazyload\"\n        alt=\"Pogo Connect erasing\"\n        title=\"Pogo Connect erasing\"\n        data-src=\"/static/9721efd4d0458dd47782bbb4431efcdf/062c0/paper-53-eraser-pogo-connect.jpg\"\n        data-srcset=\"/static/9721efd4d0458dd47782bbb4431efcdf/16841/paper-53-eraser-pogo-connect.jpg 275w,\n/static/9721efd4d0458dd47782bbb4431efcdf/50c97/paper-53-eraser-pogo-connect.jpg 550w,\n/static/9721efd4d0458dd47782bbb4431efcdf/062c0/paper-53-eraser-pogo-connect.jpg 900w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 900px) 100vw, 900px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p>Erasing tends to be one of those modes where you want precise control for fixing mistakes. The Pogo Connect is not a good tool for this unless you have a steady hand. I can’t even count the amount of times I’d press too hard on the tip and remove a large chunk of my drawing by mistake.</p>\n<h3 id=\"how-to-erase-everything-quickly\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#how-to-erase-everything-quickly\" aria-label=\"how to erase everything quickly permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>How to erase everything quickly</h3>\n<p>Sometimes you just want to clear an entire page and start over. Of course you could manually swipe over everything with the eraser, delete and create a new page, or Rewind back to blank canvas. </p>\n<p>But the quickest way to clear a page and undo everything is by press and holding on the eraser tool icon. After a few seconds you will be prompted to ”<strong>Clear Page</strong>”. Easy peasy.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pABqPEzHlsQ\"><img src=\"/a4c68e88dcd44dec8efc10699652a0dd/paper-53-clear-page.gif\" alt=\"animation showing how to erase the entire page\"></a></p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"edge-characteristics-of-papers-eraser\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#edge-characteristics-of-papers-eraser\" aria-label=\"edge characteristics of papers eraser permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Edge characteristics of Paper’s eraser</h2>\n<p>I like to compare the line qualities of the eraser to the marker (outline) and fountain pen (draw) tools. Unlike the watercolor brush or pencil tools, the eraser has a smooth and clean edge and is very binary in its application. It either removes what it touches right down to the egg shell colored background, or it doesn’t — there is no granularity.</p>\n<h3 id=\"harsh-edges-are-good-for\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#harsh-edges-are-good-for\" aria-label=\"harsh edges are good for permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Harsh edges are good for</h3>\n<p>The harsh edges produced by the eraser are great for bold illustrations, comics/cartoons, wire-framing, diagrams, and lettering. Basically anywhere you’d want to retain a smooth edge and keep the line work crisp. </p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; background-color: var(--input-background-color); max-width: 900px;\"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 56.72727272727273%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image lazyload\"\n        alt=\"examples of crisp line work\"\n        title=\"examples of crisp line work\"\n        data-src=\"/static/b0bd1f3eae934e76a165b0b50380920f/062c0/paper-53-erasing-crisp-edge.jpg\"\n        data-srcset=\"/static/b0bd1f3eae934e76a165b0b50380920f/16841/paper-53-erasing-crisp-edge.jpg 275w,\n/static/b0bd1f3eae934e76a165b0b50380920f/50c97/paper-53-erasing-crisp-edge.jpg 550w,\n/static/b0bd1f3eae934e76a165b0b50380920f/062c0/paper-53-erasing-crisp-edge.jpg 900w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 900px) 100vw, 900px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<h3 id=\"harsh-edges-are-bad-for\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#harsh-edges-are-bad-for\" aria-label=\"harsh edges are bad for permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Harsh edges are bad for</h3>\n<p>Call me biased, but I don’t think the eraser tool works well when trying to achieve a degree of <em>softness</em> in your work. I create a lot of work in the <a href=\"/paperfaces/\">photo-realistic camp</a> and find that a swipe of the eraser can destroy the textured quality of watercolor and pencil strokes. </p>\n<p>If the eraser removed strokes in a more granular way it might be a different story, but for the most part I avoid the tool like the plague. I’ve found it much easier to paint with variations of white to “erase” strokes gradually. More on that below…</p>\n<figure>\n  <span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\" style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; background-color: var(--input-background-color); max-width: 900px;\">\n      <span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\" style=\"padding-bottom: 74.9090909090909%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; display: block;\"></span>\n  <img class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image lazyload\" alt=\"erasing fur and hair can ruin the effect\" title=\"erasing fur and hair can ruin the effect\" data-src=\"/static/758f485a8461eecdb5be68880ca84f48/062c0/paper-53-eraser-fur-coverup.jpg\" data-srcset=\"/static/758f485a8461eecdb5be68880ca84f48/16841/paper-53-eraser-fur-coverup.jpg 275w,\n/static/758f485a8461eecdb5be68880ca84f48/50c97/paper-53-eraser-fur-coverup.jpg 550w,\n/static/758f485a8461eecdb5be68880ca84f48/062c0/paper-53-eraser-fur-coverup.jpg 900w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 900px) 100vw, 900px\" style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\" loading=\"lazy\">\n    </span>\n  <figcaption><p>Notice how erasing the fur strokes creates an abrupt edge making it harder to cover-up?</p></figcaption>\n</figure>\n<h2 id=\"erasing-techniques\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#erasing-techniques\" aria-label=\"erasing techniques permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Erasing techniques</h2>\n<p>If you’re like me and lust after a tool that functions like a traditional gum eraser you’re in luck. There are three <em>eraser hacks</em> I use to achieve similar results:</p>\n<h3 id=\"partially-erase-a-line\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#partially-erase-a-line\" aria-label=\"partially erase a line permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Partially erase a line</h3>\n<p>Instead of completely erasing a stroke you can partially remove it. By leaving fragments of the original, you retain the spirit of its texture and form. There will still be some “crispness” along the erased edges, but they won’t be as harsh.</p>\n<p>The easiest way to pull this off is by dabbing your finger or stylus repeatedly while using the eraser. This will lift bits and pieces of the original drawing away with each dab.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; background-color: var(--input-background-color); max-width: 900px;\"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 66.18181818181819%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image lazyload\"\n        alt=\"partially erased sketched of toddlers\"\n        title=\"partially erased sketched of toddlers\"\n        data-src=\"/static/bd65a873a82cb90216a5be137894c6c5/062c0/paper-53-eraser-dab-method.jpg\"\n        data-srcset=\"/static/bd65a873a82cb90216a5be137894c6c5/16841/paper-53-eraser-dab-method.jpg 275w,\n/static/bd65a873a82cb90216a5be137894c6c5/50c97/paper-53-eraser-dab-method.jpg 550w,\n/static/bd65a873a82cb90216a5be137894c6c5/062c0/paper-53-eraser-dab-method.jpg 900w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 900px) 100vw, 900px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p>This is especially effective during the sketching phase of creation. By leaving part of the drawing on the canvas it allows you to use it as a guide as you continually refine it.</p>\n<h3 id=\"paint-with-white-to-erase\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#paint-with-white-to-erase\" aria-label=\"paint with white to erase permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Paint with white to erase</h3>\n<p>My preferred method of “erasing” is to use the watercolor brush loaded with white. With any other color, the brush works as a multiplier building up each layer like panes of colored glass. But when you mix a pure white or tint, it becomes more opaque and acts as a cover-up tool.</p>\n<p>By taking advantage of this property, white can be used to emulate a gum eraser. By dabbing the brush on the canvas, previously painted colors will begin to lighten. The longer you linger the whiter the area will become — speed matters so work quick!</p>\n<p><div class=\"gatsby-resp-iframe-wrapper\" style=\"padding-bottom: 56.42857142857143%; position: relative; height: 0; overflow: hidden; \" > <div class=\"embedVideo-container\"> <iframe data-src=\"https://www.youtube-nocookie.com/embed/-BLKj1xww6w?rel=0\" class=\"embedVideo-iframe lazyload\" style=\"border:0; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; \" allowfullscreen></iframe> </div> </div></p>\n<p>I’ve found that using the fat side of Pencil’s tip to swipe in white allows for greater control and smoother transitions. It takes some practice as it is a more advanced technique to master.</p>\n<div class=\"custom-block notice\"><div class=\"custom-block-heading\">White to “erase” gotcha</div><div class=\"custom-block-body\"><p>This method does have a drawback. Using white to “erase” can create more work for yourself if you have a detailed background. The white might bleed into it forcing you to spend a lot of time color matching to clean-up edges. For this reason I tend to work on areas that need lightening first and cover up any messy edges later.</p></div></div>\n<h3 id=\"blend-smudge-to-erase\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#blend-smudge-to-erase\" aria-label=\"blend smudge to erase permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Blend (smudge) to erase</h3>\n<p>Another effective way of softening a sketch, is to smudge it with Blend<sup id=\"fnref-1\"><a href=\"#fn-1\" class=\"footnote-ref\">1</a></sup>. The slower you glide your finger across the screen the more intense the blur. When done correctly, lines can be partially blended away making it easier draw over — using them as a guide.</p>\n<figure>\n  <span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\" style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; background-color: var(--input-background-color); max-width: 900px;\">\n      <span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\" style=\"padding-bottom: 60%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; display: block;\"></span>\n  <img class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image lazyload\" alt=\"sketches of a face with lines blended to use as a guide\" title=\"sketches of a face with lines blended to use as a guide\" data-src=\"/static/ece2dc889f6096c61dfacfa0865a420b/062c0/paper-53-eraser-blend-guides.jpg\" data-srcset=\"/static/ece2dc889f6096c61dfacfa0865a420b/16841/paper-53-eraser-blend-guides.jpg 275w,\n/static/ece2dc889f6096c61dfacfa0865a420b/50c97/paper-53-eraser-blend-guides.jpg 550w,\n/static/ece2dc889f6096c61dfacfa0865a420b/062c0/paper-53-eraser-blend-guides.jpg 900w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 900px) 100vw, 900px\" style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\" loading=\"lazy\">\n    </span>\n  <figcaption><p><a href=\"/mastering-paper/grid-method/#removing-the-grid\">Blending away guides</a> and rough sketches is great way to disguise them for inking or painting over.</p></figcaption>\n</figure>\n<p>There’s also the option of using the eraser as you normally would followed with carefully placed Blends. You’ll want to be quick with your smudge strokes to avoid pushing pixels too far and ruining any built up textures. But with some practice you can cover-up any ill effects from the eraser.</p>\n<p>Once you get into a rhythm — bouncing between sketching, erasing, and smudging can begin to feel natural.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"additional-resources\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#additional-resources\" aria-label=\"additional resources permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Additional resources</h2>\n<p>In case you scrolled through all those words up there I put together an erasing cheat sheet below:</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; background-color: var(--input-background-color); max-width: 900px;\"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 74.9090909090909%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image lazyload\"\n        alt=\"Paper for iOS How to Erase cheat sheet\"\n        title=\"Paper for iOS How to Erase cheat sheet\"\n        data-src=\"/static/c4c39df8ce1a7c30c8b2e442eaa2eeff/062c0/mastering-paper-erasing-cheatsheet-900.jpg\"\n        data-srcset=\"/static/c4c39df8ce1a7c30c8b2e442eaa2eeff/16841/mastering-paper-erasing-cheatsheet-900.jpg 275w,\n/static/c4c39df8ce1a7c30c8b2e442eaa2eeff/50c97/mastering-paper-erasing-cheatsheet-900.jpg 550w,\n/static/c4c39df8ce1a7c30c8b2e442eaa2eeff/062c0/mastering-paper-erasing-cheatsheet-900.jpg 900w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 900px) 100vw, 900px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<h2 id=\"how-do-you-use-the-eraser-tool\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#how-do-you-use-the-eraser-tool\" aria-label=\"how do you use the eraser tool permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>How do you use the eraser tool?</h2>\n<p>Does the way that the eraser tool behave in <strong>Paper by FiftyThree</strong> work as you’d expect? Do you find it convenient having the tool integrated directly into Pencil? Feel free to share your thoughts, sketches, links to Mixes, and techniques in the comments below.</p>\n<div class=\"footnotes\">\n<hr>\n<ol>\n<li id=\"fn-1\">\n<p>Surface Pressure and Blend features require a Pencil stylus paired to Paper to enable.</p>\n<a href=\"#fnref-1\" class=\"footnote-backref\">↩</a>\n</li>\n</ol>\n</div>","excerpt":"One of those tools that is easily forgotten about is the eraser — the utensils used to make marks tend to get more attention than those that…","timeToRead":6,"tableOfContents":"<ul>\n<li>\n<p><a href=\"/mastering-paper/erasing/#eraser-tool-101\">Eraser tool 101</a></p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"/mastering-paper/erasing/#how-speed-affects-erasing\">How speed affects erasing</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/mastering-paper/erasing/#how-surface-pressure-affects-erasing\">How Surface Pressure affects erasing</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/mastering-paper/erasing/#how-pressure-sensitivity-affects-erasing\">How pressure sensitivity affects erasing</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/mastering-paper/erasing/#how-to-erase-everything-quickly\">How to erase everything quickly</a></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><a href=\"/mastering-paper/erasing/#edge-characteristics-of-papers-eraser\">Edge characteristics of Paper’s eraser</a></p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"/mastering-paper/erasing/#harsh-edges-are-good-for\">Harsh edges are good for</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/mastering-paper/erasing/#harsh-edges-are-bad-for\">Harsh edges are bad for</a></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><a href=\"/mastering-paper/erasing/#erasing-techniques\">Erasing techniques</a></p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"/mastering-paper/erasing/#partially-erase-a-line\">Partially erase a line</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/mastering-paper/erasing/#paint-with-white-to-erase\">Paint with white to erase</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/mastering-paper/erasing/#blend-smudge-to-erase\">Blend (smudge) to erase</a></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><a href=\"/mastering-paper/erasing/#additional-resources\">Additional resources</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/mastering-paper/erasing/#how-do-you-use-the-eraser-tool\">How do you use the eraser tool?</a></li>\n</ul>"},"comments":{"edges":[{"node":{"id":"5fe0525a-67e8-5711-b09e-234943c6667f","frontmatter":{"name":"Victor O Silva","email":"0d218474625037ebbd251d6486a02ee5","friendlyDate":"March 25, 2017","iso8601Date":"2017-03-25T13:49:20.597Z","published":null},"html":"<p>how do i transfer my drawings to my laptop ? When I go to my laptop and sign on\nonly a few of my drawings show up. I would very much would like to see what I do\non all my devices. Thanks.</p>"}},{"node":{"id":"10555068-c8a3-5f31-8cde-ad526488a901","frontmatter":{"name":"Michael Rose","email":"1ce71bc10b86565464b612093d89707e","friendlyDate":"March 28, 2017","iso8601Date":"2017-03-28T16:37:22.255Z","published":null},"html":"<p>Are you referring the Paper website? If yes that only shows your drawings and\nideas that you’ve specifically shared to Paper via the <strong>Public Stream</strong>. If you\ndon’t want to make them publicly available you can save them to your camera roll\n(iPad or iPhone) and then email to yourself.</p>\n<p>Or use one of the many other sharing options Paper affords via the share sheet.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://i.imgur.com/Y5vQu9G.jpg\" alt=\"iOS share sheet\"></p>"}},{"node":{"id":"1c04a762-71f0-5f42-bca0-795b32ed9e03","frontmatter":{"name":"C. J. W. Johnson","email":"3f7221396ab762e2357b98afd4526c56","friendlyDate":"July 30, 2017","iso8601Date":"2017-07-30T19:05:14.763Z","published":null},"html":"<p>Yeah, pencil just does not, nor has it ever, simply erased. I have never been\nable to just flip the thing over and erase, like with a real pencil. I have the\nblack and the maple, and neither do it. The eraser is treated just like a stylus\ntip, which makes for frustrating drawing…any ideas?</p>"}},{"node":{"id":"94e2b573-754b-5bba-839c-1eccee6bd609","frontmatter":{"name":"Michael Rose","email":"1ce71bc10b86565464b612093d89707e","friendlyDate":"July 30, 2017","iso8601Date":"2017-07-30T23:53:09.382Z","published":null},"html":"<ol>\n<li>Verify your Pencil is fully charged and\n<a href=\"https://support.fiftythree.com/hc/en-us/articles/201712591-Using-Pencil#connecting\">connected to Paper</a>.</li>\n<li>Verify your Pencil is\n<a href=\"https://support.fiftythree.com/hc/en-us/articles/201577742-Upgrading-the-Pencil-Firmware\">updated to the latest firmware</a>.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>If it’s still not erasing from the top then you probably have defective Pencils.\nI’d suggest reaching out to FiftyThree’s support for further troubleshooting.</p>"}}]}},"pageContext":{"next":{"frontmatter":{"path":"/paperfaces/nick-b-2-portrait/","title":"Winter Ready","categories":["paperfaces"],"tags":["portrait","illustration","Paper for iOS"]},"fileAbsolutePath":"/home/28041/opensource/github.com/mmistakes/made-mistakes-gatsby/src/posts/paperfaces/nick-b-2-portrait.md"},"previous":{"frontmatter":{"path":"/paperfaces/remi-l-portrait/","title":"A Beard That Hides","categories":["paperfaces"],"tags":["portrait","illustration","Paper for iOS","Sktchy","beard"]},"fileAbsolutePath":"/home/28041/opensource/github.com/mmistakes/made-mistakes-gatsby/src/posts/paperfaces/remi-l-portrait.md"}}}}